  abstract  = {Abstract The cubic polymorph of FeGe and MnSi belong to a class of magnetic intermetallic compounds with the B20 crystal structure (P213). Materials with this crystal structure lack inversion symmetry; they have chirality and are capable of supporting a long range static spin density wave at low temperature. Various aspects of the magnetic phase diagrams of FeGe and MnSi have been studied by small-angle neutron scattering and correlated to the most recent theoretical treatments. Detailed magnetization studies of both compounds have led to a re-analysis of some of the neutron diffraction data for FeGe and an extended study of MnSi, in particular of the magnetic structure in the so-called ?phase-A? near the critical temperature. For both compounds, the data are consistent with the Landau-type free energy calculations for the Dzyaloshinskii-Moriya helices. The new data for MnSi indicate that the anisotropy energy, which governs the direction of helix propagation, changes sign when passing through ?phase-A?.},
